<div id="review_1239025958" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1239025958" />
    <a title="Cassandra" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4458634-cassandra"><img alt="Cassandra" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1392941678p2/4458634.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1239025958?book_show_action=true">Mar 27, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Cassandra" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Cassandra" href="/user/show/4458634-cassandra">Cassandra</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4458634-cassandra?shelf=read-in-2015">read-in-2015</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4458634-cassandra?shelf=review-copies">review-copies</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1239025958" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12922130009290092968">ARC kindly provided by the publisher via NetGalley in exchange for an honest review.<br/><br/>Barbara&apos;s Plea felt a bit like a Hallmark/Lifetime movie. Luckily, I happen to like Lifetime movies. I&apos;m a sucker for stories in which women rise up from really horrible situations and this book definitely delivered there.<br/><br/>I did feel, however, that the characters were on extreme ends of the spectrum of good and bad. Todd was a really, really bad guy. Grey was a really, really good guy. Gloria was a really, really </span>
  <span id="freeText12922130009290092968" style="display:none">ARC kindly provided by the publisher via NetGalley in exchange for an honest review.<br /><br />Barbara's Plea felt a bit like a Hallmark/Lifetime movie. Luckily, I happen to like Lifetime movies. I'm a sucker for stories in which women rise up from really horrible situations and this book definitely delivered there.<br /><br />I did feel, however, that the characters were on extreme ends of the spectrum of good and bad. Todd was a really, really bad guy. Grey was a really, really good guy. Gloria was a really, really good woman. The people involved with Barb's escape were really, really selfless people. It even seemed that Gloria's staff were really, really good people, especially considering how much Amelia took care of Allie when I'm sure that wasn't in her job description. This isn't necessarily a bad thing, but I do appreciate characters that are more realistic, which to me means that they may do bad things but have good intentions behind them (though many don't) or they may do good things but they also sometimes mess up. People that are too perfect creep me out because it feels like they're hiding something.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12922130009290092968" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


