    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1258176689" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1258176689" />
    <a title="Kaie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8739233-kaie"><img alt="Kaie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1598599884p2/8739233.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1258176689?book_show_action=true">Apr 18, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kaie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kaie" href="/user/show/8739233-kaie">Kaie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8739233-kaie?shelf=abuse">abuse</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8739233-kaie?shelf=contemporary">contemporary</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8739233-kaie?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8739233-kaie?shelf=read-in-2015">read-in-2015</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8739233-kaie?shelf=review-copy">review-copy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8739233-kaie?shelf=netgalley">netgalley</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1258176689" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12116668575785514261"><i>* I received free digital review copy through NetGalley from publisher in exchange for an honest review.</i><br/><br/>What is it lately with me and domestic abuse novels? I have read numerous throughout this year. &apos;Although Barbara&apos;s Plea&apos; was a quick, slightly painful read handling domestic violence, I liked it least of them. <br/><br/>&apos;Barbara&apos;s Plea&apos; was about Barbara&apos;s escape from her abusive husband. Leaving an abusive person can be life threatening, so Barbara and her daughter had to flee secretly. As soon as she</span>
  <span id="freeText12116668575785514261" style="display:none"><i>* I received free digital review copy through NetGalley from publisher in exchange for an honest review.</i><br /><br />What is it lately with me and domestic abuse novels? I have read numerous throughout this year. 'Although Barbara's Plea' was a quick, slightly painful read handling domestic violence, I liked it least of them. <br /><br />'Barbara's Plea' was about Barbara's escape from her abusive husband. Leaving an abusive person can be life threatening, so Barbara and her daughter had to flee secretly. As soon as she thought she was safe she fell for another man. When was the time to heal? After a traumatizing relationship, there is a change to fall for another abuser like happened with Sara in 'Sleeping with the Enemy'. The author noticed reader's hesitations and tried to smooth them, but it sends out a wrong message. Real life is cruel, you need time to recover. <br /><br />I liked Barbara though. She was intelligent. As soon as she realized her home life was miserable she took actions to leave, not change her husband. It is another reminder, leaving an abusive partner is dangerous and it should be planned in advance to for maximum security. Characters were one-dimensional, good or bad entirely. They were given as tragic past as possible to get readers sympathize with them. At some point, it got annoying for me. And the thing which happened with Greyson's ex-wife was so American Gods, not even original. <br /><br />'Barbara's Plea' was a heavy read at times. It contains graphic violence. I had to put it down for a while and think about life. But it wasn't as suspenseful as 'Sleeping with the Enemy' or as scary as Into the Darkest Corner. At times, I cringed in embarrassment because the story was sappy. So the story or characters won't stick with me long.<br /><br />I appreciate the message that good things can happen to battered women if they let them happen and accept help. To the rest of the population, who says " just leave him," it tells it is harder than they think. <br /><br />'Barbara's Plea' was a quick read that pointed at important issues in society, but one-dimensional characters, sappiness, and predictability made it cringeworthy read I will forget soon. Unlike 'Into the Darkest Corner' that made me too frightened to read it in the dark.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12116668575785514261" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

